-- id=76: PRASA Passenger Rail Recovery Programme
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The Passenger Rail Agency of South Africa (PRASA) provides commuter rail services across nine metropolitan areas, with a pre-COVID ridership of 600 million trips annually that collapsed to under 100 million by 2023 following widespread infrastructure vandalism (3,000+ incidents between 2020 and 2022 stripped overhead electrical cables, signalling equipment, and rolling stock for copper and scrap metal). The PRASA Recovery Programme, managed through the Presidential State-Owned Entities Recovery Unit and funded through a R100 billion medium-term capital programme (R25 billion over three years), is rebuilding infrastructure: 3,500 wagons refurbished, 80 train sets reactivated on Gauteng commuter lines, security contracts with private armed response deployed across 24 priority stations. The PC on Transport BRRRs 2021–2024 document PRASA''s near-complete institutional collapse under the Popo Molefe-era irregular procurement findings (R25.7 billion in irregular expenditure) and the subsequent governance recovery under the PRASA Act administration. Ridership recovery to 300 million trips by 2027 is the operational target. This is directly linked to transport integration reform (id=84) and the EPWP programme for station precinct renewal (id=98).',
  key_quote = 'PRASA carried 600 million passengers per year before vandalism destroyed its infrastructure—restoring commuter rail is not a luxury but a basic service for 15 million low-income workers who have no affordable alternative. — PRASA Recovery Report, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'PRASA / Department of Transport / National Treasury',
  feasibility_note = 'High impact, funded. R25 billion capital allocation is committed. Security deployment is reducing vandalism. Infrastructure restoration is on a 3-year critical path. Ridership recovery requires parallel service reliability improvement.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 76;

-- id=77: Transport Economic Regulator — Operationalising the EROT Act
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The Economic Regulation of Transport Act (EROT Act, 2024) establishes the Transport Economic Regulator (TER) as a new statutory body with jurisdiction over economic regulation of transport modes including freight rail, ports, pipelines, and aviation. The TER replaces the fragmented regulatory landscape (Ports Regulator of South Africa, NERSA pipeline regulation, ACSA airport regulation) with a single-window economic regulator modelled on the UK''s Competition and Markets Authority sector regulators. The TER''s primary mandate is setting access prices for transport network infrastructure—the key mechanism enabling third-party access to Transnet Freight Rail (id=79) and port concessions (id=59 and id=80). As of 2024, the TER''s enabling regulations, board appointment, and staff complement are in progress, with the DoT targeting full operationalisation by end-2025. The MTBPS 2025 notes the TER as a key Operation Vulindlela deliverable for logistics reform. The TER''s regulatory methodology—cost-based vs. price-cap regulation, treatment of efficient capital expenditure, return on asset base calculation—will directly determine the investment attractiveness of South African transport networks.',
  key_quote = 'The Transport Economic Regulator is the missing institutional piece of South Africa''s logistics reform—without a credible access pricing authority, private investors in rail and port infrastructure cannot price their returns, and third-party access remains theoretical. — Operation Vulindlela Progress Report, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Transport / Transport Economic Regulator',
  feasibility_note = 'Quick win: TER operationalisation is on a defined timeline. Board appointment is the immediate action. Regulatory methodology design is the substantive challenge—requires econometric expertise not currently within DoT. Linked directly to Transnet PSP and port concession reforms.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 77;

-- id=78: Road Accident Fund Structural Reform
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The Road Accident Fund (RAF), a statutory insurer that compensates victims of road accidents regardless of fault, carries an actuarial liability of R600 billion (2024)—equivalent to 10% of GDP—making it the largest contingent liability on South Africa''s books after Eskom. The RAF is structurally insolvent: fuel levy revenue of R45 billion annually (2025/26) covers only current claims, while the unfunded liability grows by R50–80 billion per year as courts award increasingly large general damages. The RAF Amendment Act and the Road Accident Benefit Scheme (RABS) Bill, proposed since 2014, would replace the tort-based system with a no-fault social insurance model (fixed benefit schedules, income replacement for injured workers, functional rehabilitation rather than lump-sum damages). The reform eliminates the R20 billion in legal fees and disbursements that currently absorb 40% of the RAF''s total payments, redirecting them to claimant benefits. The PC on Transport BRRRs 2021–2024 have unanimously recommended RAF structural reform for a decade, noting that the legal profession''s opposition (protecting a R20 billion annual fee income) is the primary political obstacle. National Treasury''s fiscal risk register classifies RAF as the highest-risk contingent liability.',
  key_quote = 'A R600 billion actuarial liability growing at R70 billion per year cannot be sustained—the Road Accident Fund will either be reformed or will collapse, and the question is only which happens first. — National Treasury Fiscal Risk Statement, 2025',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Transport / Road Accident Fund / National Treasury',
  feasibility_note = 'High impact, politically blocked. RABS Bill has been stalled for a decade by legal profession opposition. Constitutional challenges to benefit capping are expected. Without reform, RAF becomes a fiscal crisis within a decade. Requires sustained political will that the GNU may provide.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 78;

-- id=83: Minibus Taxi Formalisation and Digital Integration
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'South Africa''s minibus taxi industry transports approximately 15 million passengers daily—two-thirds of all public transport users—through 250,000 vehicles operated by 16,000 taxi associations, generating an estimated R90 billion in annual revenue largely outside the formal financial and regulatory system. Taxi formalisation has been attempted through the Taxi Recapitalisation Programme (TRP, 2006), which paid scrapping allowances for old vehicles, and subsequent digitisation proposals, without achieving meaningful formalisation. The current reform agenda focuses on: mandatory electronic payment integration (the Golden Arrow/Dial-A-Ride model for taxi routes), GPS tracking and route permit digital verification through the National Public Transport Regulator, taxi industry association incorporation as Cooperatives or SOC structures (enabling access to SEFA and SITA procurement), and fare regulation within integrated transport frameworks. The R1.8 billion Taxi Relief Fund (COVID-era) demonstrated that direct financial engagement with the industry is possible. The PC on Transport BRRRs flag ongoing taxi violence (linked to route competition) and the absence of meaningful labour protection for taxi drivers as governance failures. Minibus taxi formalisation is a precondition for effective IPTN integration (id=84).',
  key_quote = 'South Africa''s taxi industry moves 15 million people a day and operates largely outside the financial system—formalisation would generate R9 billion in annual VAT revenue while extending social protection to 500,000 drivers currently in the informal economy. — National Treasury Transport Sector Analysis, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Transport / National Public Transport Regulator / SARS',
  feasibility_note = 'Long-term, politically sensitive. Taxi association violence is the safety risk of formalisation pressure. Electronic payment mandate is the most feasible first step. GPS tracking deployment underway through DoT fleet management programme. Phased approach preferred over shock formalisation.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 83;

