-- id=1: Copyright Amendment Bill — Fair Use and Digital Access Reform
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The Copyright Amendment Bill (CAB), passed by Parliament in 2022 but returned unsigned after President Ramaphosa declined assent citing AGOA-related IP concerns raised by the US USTR, is South Africa''s most contested intellectual property reform in two decades. The bill introduces a flexible fair use doctrine (replacing the closed fair dealing provisions of the Copyright Act 98 of 1978), creates a digital copyright framework for online platforms, and establishes exceptions for education, research, and persons with disabilities in line with the Marrakesh Treaty. The AGOA complication: the USTR identified the CAB''s fair use provisions as potentially inconsistent with the TRIPS Agreement three-step test, threatening preferential market access if signed. The PC on Trade BRRRs 2022–2024 document the tension between educational access advocates requiring fair use for digital learning and creative industry stakeholders (SAMRO, publishers) concerned about revenue loss. A revised CAB must satisfy TRIPS Article 13 while preserving meaningful educational fair use and implementing Marrakesh disability access commitments. The DTI and DIRCO are managing the diplomatic and legislative tracks in parallel.',
  feasibility_note = 'Medium feasibility. Legislative revision is within Parliament''s competence. AGOA diplomatic track requires USTR engagement. TRIPS compliance opinion from independent IP counsel is the prerequisite for re-introduction. Educational sector urgency creates pressure for 2025 resolution.',
  responsible_department = 'DTIC / DIRCO / Department of Arts and Culture',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 1;

-- id=2: Competition Commission Digital Markets Inquiry
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The Competition Commission launched its Online Intermediation Platforms Market Inquiry (OIPMI) in 2021, investigating market power in digital platforms including online food delivery (Uber Eats, Mr D Food), e-commerce (Takealot/Makro), app stores (Apple, Google), and online classifieds. Interim remedies issued in 2023 include mandatory listing of rival products on dominant platforms, prohibition on parity pricing clauses, and data access rights for third-party sellers. The final report (2024) recommends structural remedies modelled on the EU Digital Markets Act — including mandatory data portability, interoperability requirements, and algorithm transparency obligations. The Digital Platforms Competition Framework extends buyer power regulations (introduced in the Competition Amendment Act 2018 for agri-food markets) to digital platform markets. The PC on Trade BRRRs note the inquiry''s significance for SMME market access: over 60% of South African SMMEs report digital platforms as their primary sales channel, making platform governance a small business policy issue as much as a competition one. App store commission rates of 15–30% are specifically flagged as an excessive pricing concern under Section 8 of the Competition Act.',
  feasibility_note = 'High impact, moderate feasibility. Inquiry process complete; implementation of remedies is the next phase. Multinational platforms will contest structural remedies in the Competition Tribunal. Aligning with EU DMA provides international precedent support.',
  responsible_department = 'Competition Commission / Competition Tribunal / DTIC',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 2;

-- id=5: EV White Paper — Managed Automotive Transition
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The South African EV White Paper (2023), jointly developed by DTIC, DMRE, and the Presidency''s Operation Vulindlela unit, sets out a managed transition strategy for the automotive sector from internal combustion engine (ICE) vehicles to electric vehicles while protecting the 110,000 direct jobs and 4.9% of GDP contributed by the APDP-supported industry. The White Paper proposes: phased EV manufacturing incentives through an EV supplement to the APDP production rebate, public fleet procurement targets (20,000 government EVs by 2030), a public-private charging infrastructure rollout (3,000 chargers by 2027 under national standards), and a Just Transition plan for automotive component suppliers facing platform obsolescence. The platinum for fuel cell vehicles angle directly intersects the Green Hydrogen Strategy (id=6): SA''s PGM sector has a commercial interest in hydrogen fuel cell vehicles as an alternative EV pathway that could sustain demand for platinum-group metals. The MTBPS 2025 allocates R2.1 billion to automotive transformation through the APDP over 2026–2029. Global OEMs (BMW, Ford, VW, Toyota, Mercedes-Benz) have all signalled EV investment conditioned on APDP certainty and energy cost competitiveness.',
  feasibility_note = 'Medium-term horizon. APDP incentive extension requires National Treasury approval. EV infrastructure standards are regulatory (DTPW). Union engagement (NUMSA) on Just Transition is the political constraint. Energy cost reduction (id=20) is a precondition for competitive EV manufacturing.',
  responsible_department = 'DTIC / DMRE / Department of Transport',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 5;

-- id=10: Poultry Industry Anti-Dumping and Local Production Expansion
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'South Africa''s poultry industry — employing approximately 36,000 workers directly and another 30,000 in feed, hatcheries, and processing — is under sustained pressure from imports of bone-in chicken portions, primarily from Brazil and the EU. ITAC investigations confirmed dumping margins of 13–62% on EU imports, leading to provisional anti-dumping duties in 2022 and final determinations in 2023. The Poultry Master Plan (2019–2023, under review), a social compact between DTIC, Astral Foods, Rainbow Chicken, SARI (SA Poultry Association), and AMCU/FAWU, targeted a 25% reduction in imports and 26,000 additional jobs — partially met. The 2025 review focuses on: extending and deepening anti-dumping duties, addressing feed cost competitiveness (yellow maize and soya meal pricing affected by drought and import logistics), expanding cold chain infrastructure in rural areas, and accelerating halal certification to open the African export market. Zimbabwe, Zambia, and Mozambique represent significant near-term export opportunities as AfCFTA implementation proceeds. The PC on Agriculture BRRRs 2023–2024 flag avian influenza biosecurity and small-scale poultry producer exclusion from master plan benefits as gaps requiring attention.',
  feasibility_note = 'Quick win on duty extension — ITAC recommendation is within the Minister of Trade''s prerogative. Feed cost competitiveness requires energy reform progress. Cold chain investment requires the DSBD and IDC partnership. Export market expansion needs DIRCO support on SPS certificate recognition.',
  responsible_department = 'DTIC / ITAC / Department of Agriculture, Land Reform and Rural Development',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 10;

-- id=11: SMME Regulatory Burden Reduction
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'South Africa''s regulatory environment imposes disproportionate compliance costs on small and medium enterprises. Before the World Bank discontinued Doing Business, SA ranked poorly on starting a business, paying taxes (27 annual payments vs. OECD average of 11), and enforcing contracts (average 600 days). The SMME Regulatory Burden Reduction reform — coordinated by the Presidency''s Operation Vulindlela unit with the DSBD — targets the highest-friction touchpoints: business registration (CIPC BizPortal digitisation, targeting 1-day company registration), tax compliance (SARS SME relief packages and turnover tax simplification for firms below R1 million turnover), municipal licensing (SPLUMA compliance rationalisation), and labour law compliance costs (CCMA access for small employers). The Presidency''s Red Tape Reduction impact assessment (2024) identified an estimated 12 million regulatory-hours per year lost by SMMEs to compliance administration — equivalent to 6,000 full-time workers doing nothing but paperwork. BizPortal, live since 2020, processed fewer than 20% of new business registrations by 2024 due to poor SARS-CIPC system integration. The reform also proposes a single SMME compliance certificate valid across municipalities, reducing the multi-municipal registration burden for mobile businesses.',
  feasibility_note = 'Quick wins available: BizPortal-SARS integration is an inter-agency IT project within existing mandates. Turnover tax simplification is a Budget measure. Municipal licensing rationalisation requires SALGA cooperation. Political will exists under Operation Vulindlela framework.',
  responsible_department = 'DSBD / CIPC / SARS / Operation Vulindlela',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 11;

-- id=12: Digital Platforms Competition Framework (Buyer Power Regulations)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'Following the Competition Amendment Act 2018''s introduction of buyer power provisions for designated sectors (initially agri-food), the Competition Commission and DTIC proposed extending buyer power regulations to digital platform markets in 2024. The framework targets three platform categories: online marketplaces (where dominant platforms impose extractive commission structures on third-party sellers — Takealot charges 6–30% depending on category), app stores (where 15–30% Apple/Google commissions are under global regulatory scrutiny), and payment platforms (where interchange fee structures disproportionately affect SMME financial inclusion). South Africa''s competition law framework — recognised as among the most progressive in the Global South — already includes complex merger assessment, excessive pricing provisions (Section 8), and abuse of dominance remedies. The Digital Platforms Framework builds on Online Intermediation Platforms Market Inquiry findings (id=2) and aligns with EU Digital Markets Act standards, positioning SA as a regulatory reference for African digital markets governance. The SMME Development Committee (NCOP) flagged that high platform commissions reduce SMME e-commerce viability, directly linking digital competition policy to employment outcomes.',
  feasibility_note = 'Moderate feasibility. Buyer power extension requires amendment to Competition Act regulations — within Minister''s powers. Platform multinationals will challenge in Tribunal. EU DMA precedent strengthens SA''s legal position. Implementation requires Competition Commission capacity expansion.',
  responsible_department = 'Competition Commission / DTIC / ICASA',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 12;

-- id=13: National Lotteries Commission Governance Overhaul
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The National Lotteries Commission (NLC), which distributes approximately R3 billion annually from lottery proceeds to charitable, sports, and arts organisations, has been subject to sustained parliamentary and media scrutiny since 2019 for systemic governance failures. The Special Investigating Unit (SIU) investigation completed in 2023 identified R3.1 billion in irregular, fruitless, and wasteful expenditure across the NLC distribution portfolio — including grants to non-existent NGOs, politically connected beneficiaries, and construction projects with no charitable purpose. The NLC Amendment Act (under parliamentary development since 2022) proposes: mandatory public disclosure of all grants above R1 million, an independent NLC board with publicly nominated trustees replacing Ministerial appointments, a ring-fenced arts and culture fund with sector-governed distribution, and criminal referrals for implicated officials through the NPA. The PC on Trade BRRRs 2022–2024 consistently rank NLC among the worst-governed entities in its oversight portfolio. The reform is simultaneously a governance imperative and an arts sector recovery issue: legitimate arts and cultural organisations were excluded from NLC grants by politically connected intermediaries during the critical COVID-19 recovery period.',
  feasibility_note = 'High impact, moderate feasibility. Amendment Act is in Parliament — passage likely by 2025. SIU referrals to NPA are in process. Board restructuring removes Ministerial patronage incentive. Whistleblower protection for NLC staff is a necessary co-reform.',
  responsible_department = 'DTIC / NLC / NPA / SIU',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 13;

-- id=14: Localisation and Designation Policy for Public Procurement
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'South Africa''s designation policy requires certain product categories to be procured locally, with minimum local content thresholds (typically 70–100% of production value). Designated products include buses, rolling stock, textiles, furniture, and power pylons. The policy was severely disrupted by the Constitutional Court judgment in Afribusiness v Minister of Finance (2021), which invalidated the Preferential Procurement Regulations framework; the Public Procurement Act (2023) re-establishes it on constitutionally robust grounds. The reform target: expanding the designated products list to 25 additional categories — including solar panels, LED luminaires, agricultural implements, and PPE — implementing sector-level local content compliance monitoring through DTIC, and ensuring that the R1 trillion infrastructure programme''s tender specifications explicitly anchor localisation thresholds. The Jobs Fund estimates each percentage point increase in local content in public infrastructure procurement creates 2,400 direct manufacturing jobs. The PC on Trade BRRRs 2023–2024 flag that compliance monitoring is inadequate — departments self-certify local content without independent verification, enabling widespread non-compliance. SARS import data cross-referencing of designated products is the proposed monitoring mechanism.',
  feasibility_note = 'Quick win: Public Procurement Act (2023) provides the new legislative base. Expanded designation list requires DTIC Ministerial determination. Compliance monitoring system requires SARS-DTIC data sharing agreement. Political will is strong — localisation is ANC policy priority.',
  responsible_department = 'DTIC / National Treasury / SARS',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 14;

-- id=15: BBBEE Equity Equivalent Investment Programme (EEIP) Expansion
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The Equity Equivalent Investment Programme (EEIP), established under the B-BBEE Codes of Good Practice, allows multinationals that cannot undertake direct empowerment ownership (typically due to global stock exchange constraints) to make prescribed investments in skills development, supplier development, or enterprise development as a proxy for ownership points. Current approved EEIPs include Microsoft''s Skills to Succeed initiative, Ford''s enterprise supplier development fund, and pharmaceutical company R&D commitments. The DTIC''s EEIP Expansion proposes: sector-specific EEIP frameworks for fintech, mining services, and agro-processing; raising the minimum investment threshold (currently benchmarked at 25% of South African net value); establishing mandatory outcome monitoring with independent verification; and linking EEIP to technology transfer and skills development funding to ensure additionality beyond what companies would do commercially anyway. The reform addresses the widespread criticism that BBBEE compliance has become a formulaic checklist exercise rather than a genuine transformation instrument. The PC on Trade BRRRs note that EEIP approval backlogs at the DTIC (averaging 18 months) deter multinationals from applying, reducing transformation investment that could flow voluntarily.',
  feasibility_note = 'Moderate feasibility. EEIP framework is regulatory (Codes amendment) — within DTIC Minister''s prerogative with B-BBEE Commission concurrence. Outcome monitoring requires accredited verification agency capacity. Approval backlog reduction is an administrative quick win.',
  responsible_department = 'DTIC / B-BBEE Commission',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 15;

-- id=16: 4IR and Digital Skills Pipeline
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The Presidential Commission on the Fourth Industrial Revolution (PC4IR, 2019) estimated that 35% of South African jobs face high automation risk and that 130,000 additional ICT-skilled workers are required annually to meet digital economy demand. South Africa graduates approximately 10,000 ICT-related degree holders per year — a structural 13x gap. The 4IR and Digital Skills Pipeline reform coordinates: the National Digital and Future Skills Strategy (DHET, 2022), SETA-funded digital skills programmes (iMasFinance, WeThinkCode, HyperionDev partnerships with the MICT SETA), the Presidential Employment Stimulus EPWP digital component, and the Smart Artisan programme for rural ICT maintenance. The PC on Telecommunications and Postal Services BRRRs flag the foundational bottleneck: only 15% of public schools had functional internet connectivity by end-2024 (against the South African Connect Framework target of 80%), making digital skills investment unsustainable without parallel broadband infrastructure investment. DTPW''s Smart Port and Smart Border initiatives require 3,500 trained ICT technicians specifically. The NSF (National Skills Fund) has R3.2 billion in unspent reserves earmarked partly for digital skills bursaries that remain undisbursed due to procurement bottlenecks.',
  feasibility_note = 'High impact, medium cost. NSF unspent reserves provide ready funding. School connectivity is the infrastructure precondition — SA Connect implementation acceleration is the linked reform. SETA governance reform (id=52) is required to unblock discretionary grant disbursement for digital skills programmes.',
  responsible_department = 'DHET / MICT SETA / NSF / DTPW',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 16;

-- id=17: Anti-Dumping and Import Surveillance Modernisation
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The International Trade Administration Commission (ITAC) administers South Africa''s trade remedy system — anti-dumping, countervailing, and safeguard measures — under the International Trade Administration Act (2002). The system is under-resourced relative to its mandate: investigations average 18–24 months (against the WTO-compliant target of 12), the import surveillance unit has fewer than 15 analysts for a R1.7 trillion import base, and the SARS customs data interface is poorly integrated, causing delays in price comparison and injury determination. The modernisation reform proposes: an ITAC Capacity Enhancement Programme funded through a small levy on trade remedies collected; a real-time import surveillance system using HS code monitoring with automated price threshold alerts; integration of SARS trade microdata into ITAC''s price comparison database; and a 6-month fast-track procedure for critical industry investigations (steel, poultry, cement, chemicals). The PC on Trade BRRRs 2023–2024 note that ITAC is the enforcement backbone of every sector master plan but lacks the resources to sustain enforcement. BRICS+ trade expansion complicates the system: tariff remedy actions against BRICS partner imports require diplomatic calibration alongside technical trade law application.',
  feasibility_note = 'Quick win: ITAC capacity expansion is fiscally self-funding through the trade remedy levy mechanism. SARS data integration requires inter-agency agreement. Fast-track procedure requires ITA Act amendment — achievable in 2025 legislative programme. Strong industry demand (steel, poultry, textiles) for faster action.',
  responsible_department = 'ITAC / DTIC / SARS',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 17;

-- id=18: Automotive Production and Development Programme (APDP Phase 2) Enhancement
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The APDP (Automotive Production and Development Programme, 2013–2035) is South Africa''s primary automotive industrial policy, providing the Production Incentive (PI) and Automotive Investment Scheme (AIS) to OEMs and component manufacturers. In 2023, APDP supported R78 billion in vehicle exports (BMW, Toyota, Ford, VW, Mercedes-Benz) and approximately 110,000 direct jobs, making automotive the largest manufacturing export sector. Phase 2 enhancements address: incorporating EV production into the APDP incentive matrix (a dedicated EV supplement announced in the 2024 Budget, implemented from 2026); closing the local content loophole (SA-assembled vehicles using imported sub-assemblies claim full local content points); extending AIS to component suppliers investing in battery management systems and power electronics; and aligning APDP targets with the JET-IP commitments on automotive decarbonisation. The PC on Trade BRRRs 2023–2024 highlight that APDP''s vehicle export success masks two structural vulnerabilities: domestic new vehicle sales at 30-year lows (286,000 units in 2023), and the component supplier base''s limited capacity to transition to EV platforms within a commercially viable timeframe without targeted support.',
  feasibility_note = 'High impact, medium cost. EV supplement requires National Treasury approval and is in the 2024 Budget pipeline. Local content methodology revision requires DTIC regulation change. APDP certainty beyond 2035 is the investment signal that OEMs require for R&D commitments.',
  responsible_department = 'DTIC / National Treasury / NAAMSA',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 18;

-- id=19: BRICS+ Trade Facilitation and Alternative Payment Systems
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'South Africa assumed the BRICS chairmanship in 2023 and hosted the Johannesburg Summit that expanded the bloc to BRICS+ with Saudi Arabia, UAE, Ethiopia, Iran, Egypt, and Argentina. The trade facilitation agenda under SA''s chairmanship prioritised: local currency settlement frameworks to reduce USD dependency in intra-BRICS trade, New Development Bank (NDB, headquartered in Shanghai) expanded rand-denominated lending for infrastructure, and BRICS+ standards harmonisation for mutual recognition of product certifications and SPS measures. The MTBPS 2025 notes that BRICS+ trade accounts for 24% of SA''s total trade but 35% of mineral export value — making BRICS+ a strategically irreplaceable commercial relationship. The South African Reserve Bank''s Project Khokha 2 explored CBDC (Central Bank Digital Currency) interoperability as the settlement infrastructure. The PC on Finance BRRRs flag a structural tension: deepening BRICS+ engagement (including the Russia relationship) complicates SA''s AGOA retention, FATF greylisting exit, and diplomatic standing with the EU. Alternative payment systems development must be calibrated not to trigger secondary sanctions exposure or correspondent banking withdrawal by Western financial institutions.',
  feasibility_note = 'Medium feasibility. NDB rand-denominated lending is achievable and underway. CBDC interoperability is long-term. Geopolitical risk (US-Russia sanctions nexus) is the binding constraint on how far SA can advance alternative payment architecture without triggering financial isolation.',
  responsible_department = 'SARB / National Treasury / DIRCO / DTIC',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 19;

-- id=22: Two-Pot Pension System — Retirement Savings Architecture Reform
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The Two-Pot Retirement Savings System, enacted through the Revenue Laws Amendment Act and operational from 1 September 2024, restructures all South African retirement funds — pension, provident, and retirement annuity funds — into two components: a Savings Component (one-third of contributions, accessible via one annual withdrawal without resignation) and a Retirement Component (two-thirds of contributions, fully preserved until retirement). The reform resolves a decades-old tension between retirement preservation advocates (inadequate savings force old-age dependence on the State Old Age Pension) and liquidity advocates (South Africans face acute financial stress and will resign from employment to access retirement savings if no emergency window exists). SARS''s implementation from September 2024 was the most complex single administrative event since e-filing''s launch: the RA Retirement Fund Return required system overhaul, and tax implications (withdrawals taxed at marginal rate, not the retirement lump sum table) required mass public communication. The PC on Finance BRRRs 2024 note that R6.3 billion in savings component withdrawals occurred in the first quarter — validating demand while confirming that the administrative system held. Outstanding issues: the vesting pot (pre-reform savings) access rules and the treatment of legacy defined-benefit fund members.',
  feasibility_note = 'Implementation is underway — this is now a monitoring and fine-tuning reform. Legacy defined-benefit vesting pot access rules require further legislation. SARS capacity for withdrawals processing at scale is the operational risk. Fiscal cost (revenue loss from marginal rate vs. lump sum tax) is monitored quarterly.',
  responsible_department = 'National Treasury / SARS / FSCA / Pension Funds Adjudicator',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 22;

-- id=26: Inclusive Growth Spending Review — Reprioritising Social Grants vs. Employment
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'National Treasury''s Inclusive Growth Spending Review (2024), the most significant expenditure review since the Zero-Based Budget pilot, examines the composition of the R1.2 trillion social wage — Social Relief of Distress (SRD) grant, old age pensions, disability grants, child support, and the EPWP employment programme — through the lens of employment multiplier effects and poverty graduation outcomes. The core policy tension: South Africa''s social protection system is among the most extensive in the developing world (18 million beneficiaries receiving cash transfers), but the structure favours passive transfers over active labour market programmes that build skills and employment pathways. The review proposes: reforming the SRD grant into a Basic Income Grant with income tapers to avoid welfare cliff-edges, expanding EPWP Phase 4 with stronger skills-linked exit pathways, and redirecting R15 billion from low-multiplier public works to high-impact SMME employment subsidy via the Employment Tax Incentive (ETI). The MTBPS 2025 confirms the SRD at R370 per month — below the Food Poverty Line of R760 — pending the review''s outcome. The fiscal headroom for a Basic Income Grant (estimated R50–80 billion annually for the 8.5 million 18–59 working-age adult cohort at the Food Poverty Line) requires either new revenues or expenditure reprioritisation that the review must identify.',
  feasibility_note = 'High impact, contested fiscal feasibility. SRD-to-BIG transition cost is the binding constraint — requires either wealth tax, VAT adjustment, or significant expenditure reprioritisation. EPWP skills pathway reform is lower-cost and less contested. ETI expansion has strong evidence base and Treasury support.',
  responsible_department = 'National Treasury / SASSA / Department of Social Development / DSBD',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 26;
